00:31:37.840 --> 00:31:43.440
um and they have

00:31:41.039 --> 00:31:44.840
using open source virtualization

00:31:43.440 --> 00:31:47.840
technology they have

00:31:44.840 --> 00:31:49.360
achieved what is known as elastic

00:31:47.840 --> 00:31:52.399
computing

00:31:49.360 --> 00:31:53.919
what is elastic computing in very simple

00:31:52.399 --> 00:31:56.960
words what it means is

00:31:53.919 --> 00:31:59.679
as an end user if i'm a consumer

00:31:56.960 --> 00:32:01.360
when i start consuming cloud resources

00:31:59.679 --> 00:32:04.159
say virtual machine

00:32:01.360 --> 00:32:06.640
i can start with the base minimum that i

00:32:04.159 --> 00:32:10.159
i know that i will be using like say

00:32:06.640 --> 00:32:13.279
two vms i can start with that

00:32:10.159 --> 00:32:14.559
as my demand increases i can keep on

00:32:13.279 --> 00:32:16.799
increasing

00:32:14.559 --> 00:32:18.480
the number of vms that i'm that i'm

00:32:16.799 --> 00:32:21.840
going to use

00:32:18.480 --> 00:32:25.760
um and the key thing is that

00:32:21.840 --> 00:32:28.960
as a cloud consumer i can request

00:32:25.760 --> 00:32:31.919
any finite i can make

00:32:28.960 --> 00:32:32.799
any reasonable request for resources i

00:32:31.919 --> 00:32:36.640
can say

00:32:32.799 --> 00:32:39.360
i need a thousand vms okay and

00:32:36.640 --> 00:32:40.240
the cloud service provider can provide

00:32:39.360 --> 00:32:43.519
me those

00:32:40.240 --> 00:32:47.519
resources in a very timely manner

00:32:43.519 --> 00:32:50.640
so to me as an end user just the sheer

00:32:47.519 --> 00:32:52.320
fact that i am requesting a reasonable

00:32:50.640 --> 00:32:57.120
amount of requests like say

00:32:52.320 --> 00:32:58.240
1000 vms and whilst in a non-cloud world

00:32:57.120 --> 00:33:02.080
it would perhaps

00:32:58.240 --> 00:33:04.240
take me ages to get those provisioned

00:33:02.080 --> 00:33:07.120
and made available to me

00:33:04.240 --> 00:33:09.840
the cloud service provider is able to

00:33:07.120 --> 00:33:12.000
provide it to me in a very timely manner

00:33:09.840 --> 00:33:14.799
perhaps a few minutes

00:33:12.000 --> 00:33:16.799
i get the illusion and i'm using the

00:33:14.799 --> 00:33:19.200
word illusion here

00:33:16.799 --> 00:33:21.600
that the cloud service provider has

00:33:19.200 --> 00:33:25.679
infinite capacity

00:33:21.600 --> 00:33:29.039
so virtualization is

00:33:25.679 --> 00:33:32.480
the key is key in enabling

00:33:29.039 --> 00:33:36.399
elastic computing and in particular

00:33:32.480 --> 00:33:40.000
in giving end users the illusion

00:33:36.399 --> 00:33:44.640
that the provider has infinite capacity

00:33:40.000 --> 00:33:47.840
so in order to achieve elastic computing

00:33:44.640 --> 00:33:50.720
there are two inbuilt or

00:33:47.840 --> 00:33:52.080
there are two inbuilt features that all

00:33:50.720 --> 00:33:56.080
the major cloud service

00:33:52.080 --> 00:33:58.880
providers use okay the first one is

00:33:56.080 --> 00:33:59.200
automated provisioning and the second

00:33:58.880 --> 00:34:02.240
one

00:33:59.200 --> 00:34:06.720
is elastic operations let's

00:34:02.240 --> 00:34:09.919
try to understand what each one of these

00:34:06.720 --> 00:34:13.760
features are automated provisioning

00:34:09.919 --> 00:34:17.520
and elastic operations and how

00:34:13.760 --> 00:34:19.200
using these two features cloud service

00:34:17.520 --> 00:34:22.720
providers can provide

00:34:19.200 --> 00:34:25.760
services at scale and

00:34:22.720 --> 00:34:28.720
also in doing so give the

00:34:25.760 --> 00:34:29.440
end users the illusion that they have

00:34:28.720 --> 00:34:32.800
almost

00:34:29.440 --> 00:34:36.320
infinite capacity so the first thing

00:34:32.800 --> 00:34:39.919
is about automated provisioning

00:34:36.320 --> 00:34:42.879
automated provisioning means

00:34:39.919 --> 00:34:43.359
or in a non-cloud world what would

00:34:42.879 --> 00:34:46.639
happen

00:34:43.359 --> 00:34:47.599
is let's forget cloud computing for a

00:34:46.639 --> 00:34:50.720
minute

00:34:47.599 --> 00:34:53.280
in a non-cloud world the process

00:34:50.720 --> 00:34:55.359
by which a virtual machine like for

00:34:53.280 --> 00:34:58.640
example if i'm making a request

00:34:55.359 --> 00:34:59.760
for a virtual machine the process by

00:34:58.640 --> 00:35:02.480
which

00:34:59.760 --> 00:35:04.480
a virtual machine is allocated to the

00:35:02.480 --> 00:35:07.839
consumer

00:35:04.480 --> 00:35:11.280
may or may not be completely automated

00:35:07.839 --> 00:35:16.079
okay however in the cloud realm

00:35:11.280 --> 00:35:19.359
the process of provisioning or providing

00:35:16.079 --> 00:35:21.680
a virtual machine to a cloud consumer in

00:35:19.359 --> 00:35:25.119
response to their request

00:35:21.680 --> 00:35:26.640
is completely automated in other words

00:35:25.119 --> 00:35:29.680
when a cloud consumer

00:35:26.640 --> 00:35:32.720
is providing

00:35:29.680 --> 00:35:35.760
the the request what happens

00:35:32.720 --> 00:35:37.040
here is most of the major cloud service

00:35:35.760 --> 00:35:40.240
providers

00:35:37.040 --> 00:35:42.320
they have their own internal inter

00:35:40.240 --> 00:35:44.560
intelligent provisioning layer or

00:35:42.320 --> 00:35:47.640
automated provisioning layer

00:35:44.560 --> 00:35:50.079
what this this is part of the

00:35:47.640 --> 00:35:53.760
virtualization layer what this does

00:35:50.079 --> 00:35:55.040
is that it takes into account multiple

00:35:53.760 --> 00:35:58.240
factors

00:35:55.040 --> 00:36:01.760
and then automatically decides okay

00:35:58.240 --> 00:36:03.040
which physical machine here should the

00:36:01.760 --> 00:36:06.079
cloud consumers

00:36:03.040 --> 00:36:09.520
virtual machine sit should it be

00:36:06.079 --> 00:36:12.880
physical machine a b c

00:36:09.520 --> 00:36:17.119
or d and maybe it decides that okay

00:36:12.880 --> 00:36:21.119
the best fit for me is say server a

00:36:17.119 --> 00:36:21.119
so this process of

00:36:21.760 --> 00:36:27.760
taking in customer request

00:36:24.880 --> 00:36:28.560
taking an intelligent decision to decide

00:36:27.760 --> 00:36:30.880
where

00:36:28.560 --> 00:36:32.560
the request or where which physical

00:36:30.880 --> 00:36:35.359
machine

00:36:32.560 --> 00:36:35.760
the the virtual machine should be seated

00:36:35.359 --> 00:36:39.839
in

00:36:35.760 --> 00:36:41.359
like server a and d provisioning them is

00:36:39.839 --> 00:36:44.560
completely

00:36:41.359 --> 00:36:47.839
end to end automated there is

00:36:44.560 --> 00:36:50.960
no human intervention involved at all

00:36:47.839 --> 00:36:53.200
it is only due to the fact that

00:36:50.960 --> 00:36:55.839
the major cloud service providers have

00:36:53.200 --> 00:36:58.720
completely automated provisioning

00:36:55.839 --> 00:37:00.720
that these cloud service providers can

00:36:58.720 --> 00:37:04.400
provide or provision

00:37:00.720 --> 00:37:07.119
virtual machines running into

00:37:04.400 --> 00:37:07.599
tens of thousands daily otherwise it

00:37:07.119 --> 00:37:10.720
would

00:37:07.599 --> 00:37:11.280
simply not be possible if there was a

00:37:10.720 --> 00:37:15.440
human

00:37:11.280 --> 00:37:17.920
effort involved okay so as i said

00:37:15.440 --> 00:37:19.119
uh in automated provisioning the process

00:37:17.920 --> 00:37:22.960
of allocating

00:37:19.119 --> 00:37:27.119
configuring provisioning managing

00:37:22.960 --> 00:37:30.320
keeping a snapshot completely automated

00:37:27.119 --> 00:37:32.079
one thing to note here is that once

00:37:30.320 --> 00:37:34.160
say for example the automated

00:37:32.079 --> 00:37:37.280
provisioning layer has decided that

00:37:34.160 --> 00:37:40.960
my request or my virtual machine

00:37:37.280 --> 00:37:43.040
should sit in server a the allocation of

00:37:40.960 --> 00:37:44.079
the virtual machine to the physical

00:37:43.040 --> 00:37:47.760
machine

00:37:44.079 --> 00:37:49.200
is static that means during the life of

00:37:47.760 --> 00:37:51.440
the virtual machine

00:37:49.200 --> 00:37:54.160
it does not move around it doesn't the

00:37:51.440 --> 00:37:57.200
virtual machine doesn't move from

00:37:54.160 --> 00:38:00.960
server a to maybe b c d or

00:37:57.200 --> 00:38:03.520
e so it is static

00:38:00.960 --> 00:38:04.640
so that's one thing completely automated

00:38:03.520 --> 00:38:07.839
provisioning

00:38:04.640 --> 00:38:07.839
the second thing

00:38:08.640 --> 00:38:13.839
that cloud service providers use

00:38:11.839 --> 00:38:15.280
as a part of the virtualization

00:38:13.839 --> 00:38:19.599
capability

00:38:15.280 --> 00:38:23.760
is elastic operations the basic idea

00:38:19.599 --> 00:38:23.760
in elastic operations is that

00:38:25.119 --> 00:38:30.320
is that the assignment of a the basic

00:38:28.640 --> 00:38:33.280
idea in elastic operations

00:38:30.320 --> 00:38:34.240
is that the assignment of a virtual

00:38:33.280 --> 00:38:37.920
machine to a

00:38:34.240 --> 00:38:41.520
physical machine is not static

00:38:37.920 --> 00:38:44.839
okay and it can be controlled

00:38:41.520 --> 00:38:46.240
dynamically at runtime based on multiple

00:38:44.839 --> 00:38:49.760
factors so

00:38:46.240 --> 00:38:51.920
let me come to some of those factors in

00:38:49.760 --> 00:38:53.359
some time but let me tell you what may

00:38:51.920 --> 00:38:56.480
happen in elastic

00:38:53.359 --> 00:38:57.359
operations so again very similar like

00:38:56.480 --> 00:39:00.000
before

00:38:57.359 --> 00:39:00.400
i'm a cloud consumer and i'm requesting

00:39:00.000 --> 00:39:04.079
for

00:39:00.400 --> 00:39:06.640
a virtual machine just one i've got

00:39:04.079 --> 00:39:08.640
maybe a few others that are running but

00:39:06.640 --> 00:39:09.520
at the moment i'm just requesting for

00:39:08.640 --> 00:39:12.160
one

00:39:09.520 --> 00:39:12.880
and very similar to what i have

00:39:12.160 --> 00:39:15.359
explained in

00:39:12.880 --> 00:39:16.640
automated provisioning this request is

00:39:15.359 --> 00:39:19.920
sent to

00:39:16.640 --> 00:39:24.400
elastic operations layer and this layer

00:39:19.920 --> 00:39:28.320
says okay let based on the request

00:39:24.400 --> 00:39:30.000
let this request be handled by physical

00:39:28.320 --> 00:39:33.200
machine a

00:39:30.000 --> 00:39:35.599
so far exactly the same about

00:39:33.200 --> 00:39:36.800
what we discussed in the automated

00:39:35.599 --> 00:39:40.160
provisioning

00:39:36.800 --> 00:39:43.359
however at run time when the physical

00:39:40.160 --> 00:39:46.240
when the virtual machine is running

00:39:43.359 --> 00:39:46.880
in elastic operations layer what it does

00:39:46.240 --> 00:39:49.440
it is

00:39:46.880 --> 00:39:51.119
keeps an eye out on the performance of

00:39:49.440 --> 00:39:53.560
the virtual machine

00:39:51.119 --> 00:39:55.119
perhaps this virtual machine is

00:39:53.560 --> 00:39:57.839
communicating

00:39:55.119 --> 00:39:58.560
with a few other virtual machines

00:39:57.839 --> 00:40:02.320
sitting in

00:39:58.560 --> 00:40:05.119
in machine c or maybe

00:40:02.320 --> 00:40:05.599
this physical machine where this virtual

00:40:05.119 --> 00:40:09.520
machine

00:40:05.599 --> 00:40:12.000
is sitting it seems that its performance

00:40:09.520 --> 00:40:14.160
is degrading in other words its looks

00:40:12.000 --> 00:40:17.280
like its going to fail

00:40:14.160 --> 00:40:21.200
so in elastic operations

00:40:17.280 --> 00:40:22.240
what may happen in elastic operations

00:40:21.200 --> 00:40:25.520
what may happen

00:40:22.240 --> 00:40:27.200
is the elastic operations layer keeps an

00:40:25.520 --> 00:40:28.880
eye out for the performance of the

00:40:27.200 --> 00:40:31.680
virtual machine

00:40:28.880 --> 00:40:32.800
or its communication latency and

00:40:31.680 --> 00:40:35.839
bandwidth

00:40:32.800 --> 00:40:38.480
and if it decides that it may need to

00:40:35.839 --> 00:40:40.000
move it from one physical machine like

00:40:38.480 --> 00:40:43.440
machine a

00:40:40.000 --> 00:40:46.640
to machine d so this process

00:40:43.440 --> 00:40:49.280
of moving from one machine

00:40:46.640 --> 00:40:51.760
physical machine a moving a virtual

00:40:49.280 --> 00:40:55.119
machine from physical machine a

00:40:51.760 --> 00:40:58.480
to physical machine d is

00:40:55.119 --> 00:41:01.599
possible and happens in elastic

00:40:58.480 --> 00:41:04.800
operations this process of moving

00:41:01.599 --> 00:41:05.440
from one machine to another machine is

00:41:04.800 --> 00:41:08.640
known as

00:41:05.440 --> 00:41:11.760
virtual machine migration

00:41:08.640 --> 00:41:12.880
okay you may be wondering why would you

00:41:11.760 --> 00:41:16.400
need to migrate

00:41:12.880 --> 00:41:19.680
why does one need to migrate there are

00:41:16.400 --> 00:41:21.920
plethora of reasons maybe

00:41:19.680 --> 00:41:23.040
the original virtual machine as was

00:41:21.920 --> 00:41:26.400
sitting in

00:41:23.040 --> 00:41:28.640
uh in physical machine a

00:41:26.400 --> 00:41:29.839
maybe the elastic operations layer has

00:41:28.640 --> 00:41:32.000
found out

00:41:29.839 --> 00:41:32.880
that the performance of the physical

00:41:32.000 --> 00:41:36.160
machine a

00:41:32.880 --> 00:41:38.240
is degrading and hence

00:41:36.160 --> 00:41:40.480
because it is degrading it wants to

00:41:38.240 --> 00:41:43.680
migrate it proactively

00:41:40.480 --> 00:41:47.200
before the machine degrade before the

00:41:43.680 --> 00:41:50.319
physical machine a stops functioning

00:41:47.200 --> 00:41:50.960
another option is or another reason is

00:41:50.319 --> 00:41:53.280
that

00:41:50.960 --> 00:41:55.359
it may be the case that this virtual

00:41:53.280 --> 00:41:57.520
machine which was sitting in machine

00:41:55.359 --> 00:41:57.520
a

00:41:58.960 --> 00:42:02.480
was communicating with a lot of virtual

00:42:01.760 --> 00:42:05.520
machines

00:42:02.480 --> 00:42:08.000
sitting in physical machine d

00:42:05.520 --> 00:42:08.960
and because it was communicating it was

00:42:08.000 --> 00:42:12.079
experiencing

00:42:08.960 --> 00:42:15.200
latency and perhaps delays

00:42:12.079 --> 00:42:16.000
so to stop that it says okay given that

00:42:15.200 --> 00:42:17.920
you have got a lot

00:42:16.000 --> 00:42:19.040
of virtual machines in this physical

00:42:17.920 --> 00:42:21.920
machine

00:42:19.040 --> 00:42:24.000
let me move it closer to where all the

00:42:21.920 --> 00:42:27.839
virtual machines are

00:42:24.000 --> 00:42:28.400
okay alternatively it may be the case

00:42:27.839 --> 00:42:31.520
that

00:42:28.400 --> 00:42:34.720
a new request has come in and

00:42:31.520 --> 00:42:37.760
and that new request is for a

00:42:34.720 --> 00:42:41.000
for a large number of virtual machines

00:42:37.760 --> 00:42:44.480
so what it can do is it can

00:42:41.000 --> 00:42:46.680
consolidate using

00:42:44.480 --> 00:42:48.319
virtual machine migration it can

00:42:46.680 --> 00:42:51.920
consolidate

00:42:48.319 --> 00:42:54.400
the existing workloads or existing

00:42:51.920 --> 00:42:57.359
virtual machine workloads

00:42:54.400 --> 00:42:58.160
into a smaller number of physical

00:42:57.359 --> 00:43:01.760
machines

00:42:58.160 --> 00:43:03.359
as in what it can do is all the existing

00:43:01.760 --> 00:43:06.560
workloads in say machine

00:43:03.359 --> 00:43:07.119
a and machine b they can take this and

00:43:06.560 --> 00:43:10.160
move it

00:43:07.119 --> 00:43:12.480
only to c and d and make

00:43:10.160 --> 00:43:13.599
machine physical machine a and physical

00:43:12.480 --> 00:43:17.440
machine be

00:43:13.599 --> 00:43:21.599
available for new requests so you see

00:43:17.440 --> 00:43:24.720
the whole essence of elastic operations

00:43:21.599 --> 00:43:28.079
which is to move virtual machines

00:43:24.720 --> 00:43:30.560
across at run time

00:43:28.079 --> 00:43:31.800
gives cloud service providers the

00:43:30.560 --> 00:43:34.800
ability to

00:43:31.800 --> 00:43:37.920
consolidate existing

00:43:34.800 --> 00:43:39.760
virtual machine loads onto a smaller set

00:43:37.920 --> 00:43:43.680
of physical machines

00:43:39.760 --> 00:43:47.280
and hence for you and i it almost

00:43:43.680 --> 00:43:48.640
gives the illusion that if i put in any

00:43:47.280 --> 00:43:52.000
reasonable request

00:43:48.640 --> 00:43:54.160
for virtual machines that request will

00:43:52.000 --> 00:43:55.440
not be declined because they can always

00:43:54.160 --> 00:43:59.359
consolidate

00:43:55.440 --> 00:44:02.720
and they can create new capacity for me

00:43:59.359 --> 00:44:05.920
okay so this process as i said

00:44:02.720 --> 00:44:08.160
uh the process of migrating from one

00:44:05.920 --> 00:44:09.200
physical machine to another physical

00:44:08.160 --> 00:44:11.359
machine

00:44:09.200 --> 00:44:13.280
as i explained is known as virtual

00:44:11.359 --> 00:44:16.319
machine migration

00:44:13.280 --> 00:44:19.280
and if the underlying physical machines

00:44:16.319 --> 00:44:22.079
are very large and cloud service

00:44:19.280 --> 00:44:23.440
providers they have physical machines in

00:44:22.079 --> 00:44:25.839
a data center

00:44:23.440 --> 00:44:26.800
running into perhaps hundreds of

00:44:25.839 --> 00:44:30.160
thousands

00:44:26.800 --> 00:44:32.240
okay and with

00:44:30.160 --> 00:44:35.920
with virtual machine migration they can

00:44:32.240 --> 00:44:36.640
consolidate workloads into a smaller set

00:44:35.920 --> 00:44:39.440
of

00:44:36.640 --> 00:44:40.480
physical machines then for the cloud

00:44:39.440 --> 00:44:43.520
consumers we

00:44:40.480 --> 00:44:47.040
we almost get the illusion or feeling of

00:44:43.520 --> 00:44:51.440
infinite capacity okay

00:44:47.040 --> 00:44:54.800
so this virtual machine migration

00:44:51.440 --> 00:44:55.119
is a process that is very commonly used

00:44:54.800 --> 00:44:58.400
by

00:44:55.119 --> 00:45:01.200
most major cloud service providers

00:44:58.400 --> 00:45:03.760
depending upon the actual process

00:45:01.200 --> 00:45:05.599
involved in virtual machine migration as

00:45:03.760 --> 00:45:08.720
a consumer

00:45:05.599 --> 00:45:12.960
you may or you may not notice that

00:45:08.720 --> 00:45:16.400
your vm is being migrated there are

00:45:12.960 --> 00:45:18.160
at least four steps involved in virtual

00:45:16.400 --> 00:45:21.760
machine migration

00:45:18.160 --> 00:45:25.200
so say if i am interacting with

00:45:21.760 --> 00:45:27.599
aws ec2 and that is running on a

00:45:25.200 --> 00:45:30.160
physical machine of course

00:45:27.599 --> 00:45:31.280
and that needs to be migrated the first

00:45:30.160 --> 00:45:34.560
thing that will happen

00:45:31.280 --> 00:45:37.839
is it'll suspend the virtual machine's

00:45:34.560 --> 00:45:39.680
execution so all the execution that's

00:45:37.839 --> 00:45:41.599
being done and all of those things it

00:45:39.680 --> 00:45:44.800
will stop it there

00:45:41.599 --> 00:45:47.359
and it will also suspend me

00:45:44.800 --> 00:45:48.160
as a user it will suspend any

00:45:47.359 --> 00:45:53.040
interaction

00:45:48.160 --> 00:45:55.440
so i can perhaps keep on giving requests

00:45:53.040 --> 00:45:57.440
but these requests are not reaching the

00:45:55.440 --> 00:45:59.200
virtual machine they are just being

00:45:57.440 --> 00:46:02.880
